---
import DocLayout from '../layouts/DocLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';

// Key:
//   ph-generic  → bashGeneric   RGB(208,26,20)    red
//   ph-var      → variables     RGB(0,75,0)       dark green
//   ph-type     → types         Blue
//   ph-class    → classes       Orange
//   ph-fn       → functions     Orchid
//   ph-exec     → executables   RGB(255,102,178)  pink
//   ph-file     → fileNames     NavyBlue
//   ph-dir      → directories   Green

// ── 2.1 Installation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const verifyRosCode = `ls /opt/ros/`;

const installNumPyCode = `sudo apt install python3-numpy`;

const verifyEigenCode = `whereis eigen3`;

const installEigenCode = `sudo apt-get install libeigen3-dev`;

const installPinocchioCode = `sudo apt install ros-jazzy-pinocchio`;

// ── 2.2 Setup Development Environment ───────────────────────────────────────
const sourceRosCode = `source /opt/ros/jazzy/setup.bash`;

const cdHomeCode = `cd ~`;

const openBashrcCode = `gedit .bashrc`;

const installGeditCode = `sudo apt install gedit`;

const appendBashrcCode = `source /opt/ros/jazzy/setup.bash`;

const makeWorkspaceCode = `mkdir [workspace_name]`;
const makeWorkspaceCustom = `mkdir <span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span>`;

const enterWorkspaceCode =
`cd [workspace_name]
mkdir src`;
const enterWorkspaceCustom =
`cd <span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span>
mkdir src`;

const buildWorkspaceCode =
`cd ..
colcon build`;

const linkSingleCode = `ln -s [source_directory] [target_directory]`;
const linkSingleCustom = `ln -s <span class="ph-dir">[source_directory]</span> <span class="ph-dir">[target_directory]</span>`;

const linkAllCode = `ln -s [source_directory]/* [target_directory]`;
const linkAllCustom = `ln -s <span class="ph-dir">[source_directory]</span>/* <span class="ph-dir">[target_directory]</span>`;

const linkDirsCode = `ln -s [source_directory]/*/ [target_directory]`;
const linkDirsCustom = `ln -s <span class="ph-dir">[source_directory]</span>/*/ <span class="ph-dir">[target_directory]</span>`;

const sourceLocalWorkspaceCode = `source /install/setup.bash`;

const openBashrcPackagesCode =
`cd ~
gedit .bashrc`;

const appendBashrcPackagesCode = `source ~/[directory_to_workspace]/[workspace_name]/install/setup.bash`;
const appendBashrcPackagesCustom = `source ~/<span class="ph-dir">[directory_to_workspace]</span>/<span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span>/install/setup.bash`;

const openVscodeCode =
`cd ~/[directory_to_workspace]/[workspace_name]
code .`;
const openVscodeCustom =
`cd ~/<span class="ph-dir">[directory_to_workspace]</span>/<span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span>
code .`;

// ── 2.3 Updating ROS 2 Packages ──────────────────────────────────────────────
const updatePackagesCode =
`sudo rosdep init
rosdep update
sudo apt update
sudo apt dist-upgrade`;
---

<DocLayout title="ROS 2 Installation &amp; Setup" activeSection="setup">

  <h1 class="doc-title">ROS 2 Installation &amp; Setup</h1>
  <p class="doc-subtitle">Chapter 2</p>

  <h2 class="section-heading" id="installation">
    2.1 Installation
  </h2>

  <p>Follow the Jazzy installation guide provided by the developers of ROS 2 <a href="https://docs.ros.org/en/jazzy/Installation.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">here</a>. Once you finish, you can verify the version you have installed by using the command:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={verifyRosCode} lang="bash" />

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.1.1 Installing NumPy (Python)</h3>
  <p>NumPy is a high-performance Python library for scientific computation. <strong>Using NumPy is optional but highly recommended within your robotic software.</strong></p>

  <CodeBlock code={installNumPyCode} lang="bash" />

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.1.2 Installing Eigen3 (C++)</h3>
  <p>Eigen3 is a high-performance C++ library for scientific computation. <strong>Using Eigen3 is optional but highly recommended within your robotic software.</strong></p>
  <p>Eigen3 should already come with ROS 2 Jazzy. You can verify that is the case through:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={verifyEigenCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>If Eigen3 is not yet installed, perform the following:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={installEigenCode} lang="bash" />

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.1.3 Installing Pinocchio</h3>
  <p>Pinocchio is a fast kinematics and dynamics library for robotics. <strong>Using Pinocchio is optional; there are several other libraries which accomplish the same goal.</strong> It is available for both Python and C++.</p>

  <CodeBlock code={installPinocchioCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>This will install the C++ library as well as the Python bindings for ROS 2 Jazzy.</p>

  <h2 class="section-heading" id="setup-environment">
    2.2 Setup Development Environment
  </h2>

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.2.1 Sourcing Terminals</h3>
  <p>Every terminal you open must source the setup.bash file located at /opt/ros/jazzy. <strong>If you don't do this, the terminal will not be able to recognize ROS commands.</strong></p>
  <p>When opening a new terminal, source it by running:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={sourceRosCode} lang="bash" />

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">2.2.1.1 Shortcut to Sourcing Terminals</h4>
  <p>Sourcing every time you open a new terminal is tedious. You can avoid this by modifying the .bashrc file that is located in your home directory. If you are not in your home directory, use:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={cdHomeCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>Then open the .bashrc file by using:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={openBashrcCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>If you don't have gedit install, run:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={installGeditCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>At the end of the file, add:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={appendBashrcCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>Save the file and close it (Control-X then enter). bashrc will now run automatrically every time you open a new terminal.</p>

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.2.2 Creating Workspaces</h3>
  <p>You can create a workspace where you will store relevant packages where ever you like. Its name, <code class="param-name ph-generic-inline">[workspace_name]</code>, can be anything that is convenient.</p>

  <CodeBlock code={makeWorkspaceCode} lang="bash" customHtml={makeWorkspaceCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <p>Enter the directory and create a /src directory.</p>

  <CodeBlock code={enterWorkspaceCode} lang="bash" customHtml={enterWorkspaceCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <p>Go back to the workspace directory and run an initial build of the workspace.</p>

  <CodeBlock code={buildWorkspaceCode} lang="bash" />

  <p><strong>NOTE: you must always be in the workspace directory <strong><code class="path-inline">~/<span class="ph-dir">[directory_to_workspace]</span>/<span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span></code></strong>.</strong></p>

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.2.3 Creating Symbolic Links to Source Code</h3>
  <p>It is sometimes useful to have a separate directory to store source code to keep it neatly organized (or to store on the cloud, like GitHub), but also have the packages that we need within our workspace. Or, it is also possible that one script is shared between workspaces and packages. We can thus create symbolic links between our separate directory to our workspaces.</p>

  <div class="param-list">
    <div class="param-item">
      <code class="param-name ph-dir-inline">[source_directory]</code>
      <span class="param-desc">The original, <strong>absolute</strong> directory of the source code.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="param-item">
      <code class="param-name ph-dir-inline">[target_directory]</code>
      <span class="param-desc">The <strong>absolute</strong> directory where you want to create a symbolic link to the source code.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">2.2.3.1 Linking a Single Source Directory</h4>
  <CodeBlock code={linkSingleCode} lang="bash" customHtml={linkSingleCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">2.2.3.2 Linking All Components Within a Source Directory</h4>
  <p>This includes all of the directories and files within <code class="param-name ph-dir-inline">[source_directory]</code>.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={linkAllCode} lang="bash" customHtml={linkAllCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h4 class="subsection-heading">2.2.3.3 Linking All Directories Within a Source Directory</h4>
  <p>This only links the directories found within <code class="param-name ph-dir-inline">[source_directory]</code>.</p>
  <CodeBlock code={linkDirsCode} lang="bash" customHtml={linkDirsCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.2.4 Sourcing Installed Packages</h3>
<p>
  Every time you wish to use a package installed within a workspace, you will need to source the <strong><code class="path-inline">setup.bash</code></strong> file located in the 
  <strong><code class="path-inline">~/<span class="ph-dir">[directory_to_workspace]</span>/<span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span>/install</code></strong> directory.
</p>
<p>Every time you open a terminal, you must run the following from your workspace directory:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={sourceLocalWorkspaceCode} lang="bash" />

  <p><strong>NOTE: the following is optional</strong>.</p>
  <p>To avoid this, open the .bashrc file (from your home directory).</p>

  <CodeBlock code={openBashrcPackagesCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>Add the following line to the end of the script:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={appendBashrcPackagesCode} lang="bash" customHtml={appendBashrcPackagesCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <p>Make sure to include the appropriate global directory of the setup.bash file. If you are unsure about what that is, you can navigate to the setup.bash file and copy its directory.</p>
  <p><strong>NOTE: when working in different workspaces, you will need to change this bash command to the appropriate workspace. If not, you will be sourcing the wrong workspace.</strong></p>

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">2.2.5 Opening VSCode in Workspace</h3>
  <p>Open VSCode in your workspace directory <strong><code class="path-inline">~/<span class="ph-dir">[directory_to_workspace]</span>/<span class="ph-generic">[workspace_name]</span></code></strong>.</p>

  <CodeBlock code={openVscodeCode} lang="bash" customHtml={openVscodeCustom} showLegend={true} />

  <h2 class="section-heading" id="updating-packages">
    2.3 Updating ROS 2 Packages
  </h2>

  <p>You may use the following to check for and install any updates to ROS 2 packages:</p>

  <CodeBlock code={updatePackagesCode} lang="bash" />

</DocLayout>